  "prompt": "Can a US president quit his job out of stress and frustration?",
  "response": "Yes, a U.S. president can resign from office, and this has happened once in American history. President Richard Nixon resigned on August 9, 1974, amidst the Watergate scandal, although his resignation was not directly due to stress or frustration but rather to avoid likely impeachment and removal from office.\n\nIf a president were to resign due to stress, frustration, or any other reason, the process would follow the same constitutional framework. According to the U.S. Constitution, the vice president would assume the presidency upon the president's resignation. This is outlined in the **25th Amendment**, which provides clarity on the succession process.\n\nThe decision to resign would be personal and voluntary, but it would have significant constitutional and political implications. Historically, presidents have chosen to remain in office despite facing immense stress and challenges, as the role is considered a duty they were elected to fulfill. However, resignation remains a legal and constitutional option.",
